      "citation_id": "[CITATION_1]",
      "span_text": "Recent studies suggested that silent mating-type information regulation 2 homolog 3 (Sirt3), plays a key role in regulating mtROS homeostasis. Sirt3 is targeted to the mitochondrial matrix where it orchestrates mitochondrial oxidative metabolism, such as the TCA cycle and oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS), through deacetylation of a variety of substrates."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_2]",
      "span_text": "Intriguingly, Sirt3 also governs the level of mtROS by deacetylation of the major mitochondrial antioxidant enzymes, including manganese superoxide dismutase (SOD2), isocitrate dehydrogenase 2 (IDH2) and glutathione peroxidase (GSH-Px), as well as the components for mtROS generation in the electron transport chain (ETC) such as complex I and complex III. Moreover, it has been reported that Sirt3 functions as a downstream target of peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor (PPARγ) coactivator-1α (PGC-1α), which is directly regulated by adenosine monophosphate-activated protein kinase (AMPK), thereby stimulating deacetylation of mitochondrial enzymes involved in mtROS homeostasis and activation of forkhead box O3A (FoxO3A)-mediated mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) transcription to attenuate oxidative damage. Recent work highlights the critical importance of Sirt3 in the regulation of energetic metabolism by RSV treatment in the liver through stimulating complex I activity. Thus, we hypothesized that RSV could attenuate oxidative injury in endothelial cells via mtROS homeostasis regulation through Sirt3 signaling pathway."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_3]",
      "span_text": "Intriguingly, Sirt3 also governs the level of mtROS by deacetylation of the major mitochondrial antioxidant enzymes, including manganese superoxide dismutase (SOD2), isocitrate dehydrogenase 2 (IDH2) and glutathione peroxidase (GSH-Px), as well as the components for mtROS generation in the electron transport chain (ETC) such as complex I and complex III. Moreover, it has been reported that Sirt3 functions as a downstream target of peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor (PPARγ) coactivator-1α (PGC-1α), which is directly regulated by adenosine monophosphate-activated protein kinase (AMPK), thereby stimulating deacetylation of mitochondrial enzymes involved in mtROS homeostasis and activation of forkhead box O3A (FoxO3A)-mediated mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) transcription to attenuate oxidative damage. Recent work highlights the critical importance of Sirt3 in the regulation of energetic metabolism by RSV treatment in the liver through stimulating complex I activity. Thus, we hypothesized that RSV could attenuate oxidative injury in endothelial cells via mtROS homeostasis regulation through Sirt3 signaling pathway."
